{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480222"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:39:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:39:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"26"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/26"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.19,0.07,0.63,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"26"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75443"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/26"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"26"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60953"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"104"},{"type":"tags","id":"478"},{"type":"tags","id":"1034"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4608"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3001"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44744"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75443"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of worsening shortness of breath and central chest pain. The pain is sharp and rated as 9/10 in severity. She has a medical history of congestive cardiac failure, type 2 diabetes mellitus and lung cancer, with her last oncology review three months ago. Her medications include furosemide, metformin, and aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 112/min, blood pressure 98/64 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is pitting oedema to the knees bilaterally. A 12-lead ECG demonstrates low QRS complex height overall, with alternating heights between consecutive complexes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to be diagnostic?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum NT pro-BNP levels","CT pulmonary angiogram","Chest x-ray","Transthoracic echocardiogram","Serial troponin T levels"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of cardiac tamponade, including hypotension, tachycardia, and electrical alternans on ECG. Electrical alternans refers to beat-to-beat variation in QRS complex amplitude and is caused by the heart swinging in a fluid-filled pericardial sac. While not sensitive, it is highly specific for pericardial effusion with tamponade. The presence of lung cancer raises concern for a malignant pericardial effusion. \u003Cstrong\u003ETransthoracic echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is the investigation of choice as it can directly visualise pericardial fluid and assess for right ventricular diastolic collapse, which confirms the diagnosis of tamponade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum NT pro-BNP levels\u003C/strong\u003E would be elevated in this patient due to her known heart failure, but would not help diagnose the acute presentation. While useful in diagnosing new heart failure, it adds little value in a patient with known cardiac dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if pulmonary embolism was suspected. While this patient has risk factors for PE (malignancy, age), the presence of electrical alternans makes tamponade more likely as the primary diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest x-ray\u003C/strong\u003E may show an enlarged cardiac silhouette in pericardial effusion but is neither sensitive nor specific for tamponade. While it might show other pathology such as pulmonary oedema or malignant progression, it cannot confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerial troponin T levels\u003C/strong\u003E are useful in diagnosing acute coronary syndrome but would likely be elevated in this case due to multiple factors including heart failure and possible demand ischaemia. The ECG changes are more consistent with tamponade than acute ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Electrical alternans on ECG is highly specific for cardiac tamponade and requires urgent echocardiographic assessment","Cardiac tamponade can present with Beck\u0027s triad (hypotension, muffled heart sounds and elevated JVP), however these may not always be present or obvious on clinical examination.","Malignancy is a common cause of pericardial effusion and subsequent tamponade"],"references":["Adler Y, Charron P, Imazio M, et al. 2015 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and management of pericardial diseases. Eur Heart J. 2015;36(42):2921-64. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26320112/","Kashyap JR, Kumar S. Demonstrating the mechanism of electrical alternans in cardiac tamponade: \u201cthe swinging heart.\u201dMedical journal of Australia. 2020 Jun;213(2):66. Available at: https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2020/213/2/demonstrating-mechanism-electrical-alternans-cardiac-tamponade-swinging-heart"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60953"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"26"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60953"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T20:18:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T20:18:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"26"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75443"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG